  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 3e1cd92da80c7495a8fe7eb91fa80c2f, type: 3}
  m_Name: Fern
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::Plants.PlantData
  displayName: Fern
  audioClip: {fileID: 8300000, guid: 1ab9af716d006944aa3e7d717d78ebf9, type: 3}
  environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  poem:
    text: "In May it rains\nFerns unfurls in light green color,\nBut when?\n\n\u2014
      Matsuo Basho"
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  contextInfos:
  - text: "The Author Bash\u014D was not yet Bash\u014D when he wrote it. He was
      T\u014Dsei, the unripe peach, watching a fern slowly unfurling. Ultimately
      asking the question of himself."
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  - text: "Ode to Bamboo \u2014 Huang Tingjian (Excerpt)\n\u8568\u82BD\u521D\u653E\u5C0F\u513F\u62F3\u3002\nFern
      buds barely unfurling \u2014 like a small child's fist."
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  - text: 'Fern in Baltic Culture

      In baltic tradition the Ferns flower is
      essential to summer Solstice. Finding a flowering fern is said to come with
      wealth and knowledge, like abilities to talk to animals or read minds. The
      idea was that fern is so mystical that it only opens its flower on midnight
      of the longest day of the year.


      Further there are also romatic connotations.
      Young couples going to the forest alone to "look for the fern flower" was a
      euphemism for intimacy. This tradition was also a way to get around societal
      regulations on who to marry.'
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  - text: "K\u0101rlis Skalbe \u2014 _Papardes zieds_ (also known as _J\u0101\u0146u
      pasaka_, _Midsummer Tale_)\nLoose English:\n\n\"Let's go look for the fern
      flower,\" the boy said, and his breath caught. For the fern flower appeared
      only on J\u0101\u0146i night, a brief moment between evening's afterglow and
      morning's light, and whoever finds it is happy. \"Let's go,\" the girl whispered
      as quietly as the darkness in the forest. Hand in hand, they crept under the
      alder branches, still sweetly flushed from the evening sun\u2026 Bending down,
      they groped with their hands through the forest darkness and parted the fern
      clumps. They found glow-worms there and placed them on each other's palms like
      drops of diamond. But the fern flower was not there. And somehow, as they bent
      among the bushes, they no longer sought the flower, but only each other's hands.
      They grew confused and stopped facing one another, close, close. Their breath
      met \u2014 and what a wonder \u2014 when lips drew near to lips, it was as
      though the fern flower had bloomed between them\u2026\""
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
